{"title_page": "Metropolitan Tower (Chicago)", "text_new": "[[File:Metropolitan Tower, Chicago in May 2016.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Metropolitan Tower in 2016]]\n'''The Metropolitan Tower''', owned by Metropolitan Properties of Chicago,<ref>{{cite web | title = Britannica building to go condo | work = Chicago Business | publisher = Crain's | date = 2004-06-12 | url = http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=12816&seenIt=1 | accessdate = 2007-11-15 }}</ref> is a [[skyscraper]] located at 310 [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|S. Michigan Avenue]] in [[Chicago|Chicago's]] East [[Chicago Landmark]] [[Historic Michigan Boulevard District]] in the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] in [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], [[Illinois]], United States and has been renovated as a [[condominium]] complex with 242 units.<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\">{{cite news | last = Nunn | first = Emily | title = Blue light special | work = Chicago Tribune| pages = 5:1, 9 | publisher = Tribune Company | date = 2007-11-15 | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/lifestyle/chi-1115accessbeehivenov15,1,370570.story?coll=chi_mezz | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>  Residences range in size from {{convert|1200|sqft|m2}} to {{convert|4000|sqft|m2}}. [[Penthouse apartment|Penthouses]] feature 360 degree city views and private elevators.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Metropolitan Tower |work=Development Details |publisher=Condodomain |date=2006 |url=http://chicago.condodomain.com/user/condos/The-Metropolitan-Tower/1077 |accessdate=2007-11-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913183341/http://chicago.condodomain.com/user/condos/The-Metropolitan-Tower/1077 |archivedate=2007-09-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Prices run from $300,000 for a {{convert|762|sqft|m2}} one-bedroom unit to $1.365 million for a {{convert|1932|sqft|m2}} three-bedroom.<ref>''Chicago Magazine'', January 2005</ref>  The Metropolitan Tower is also home for a branch of [[Chase (bank)|Chase Bank]].\n\n== History ==\nDesigned by [[Graham, Anderson, Probst & White]], the Metropolitan Tower was named the Straus Building when completed in 1924.  Though it was the first building in Chicago with 30 or more floors, it was never officially designated [[List of tallest buildings in Chicago|Chicago's tallest building]] since the [[Chicago Temple Building]], also completed in 1924, is taller by {{convert|92|ft|m}} but has seven fewer floors.<ref name=\"temple\">{{cite web | title = Chicago Temple Building | work = Emporis | publisher = Emporis.com | date = 2007 | url = http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=chicagotemplebuilding-chicago-il-usa | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>  The Straus Building and the Chicago Temple Building were the first to take advantage of the 1923 [[zoning]] ordinance; before then, no building in Chicago could be taller than {{convert|260|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite book |last= Wolfe |first= Gerard R.|title= Chicago In and Around the Loop; Walking Tours of Architecture and History |edition=Second |year=2004 |publisher= McGraw-Hill}}</ref>\n\nThe Metropolitan Tower was at one time called the [[CNA Center|Continental National Insurance Company]] Building (later [[CNA Center|Continental Center I]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forums.tannerworld.com/showthread.php?t=7602 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911235110/http://forums.tannerworld.com/showthread.php?t=7602 |archivedate=2007-09-11 }}</ref>).  From 1980 to 2004 it was called the [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|Britannica Building]] when that company was its tenant.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web | title = Metropolitan Tower | work = Emporis | publisher = Emporis.com | date = 2007 | url = http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=metropolitantower-chicago-il-usa | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics, past and present ==\nThis U-shaped building, standing at {{convert|475|ft|m}} in height, fronts Chicago's [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] and [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]].  The {{convert|40|ft|m|0|adj=on}} [[pyramid]] at the top of the building (which Schulze & Harrington, authors of ''Chicago's Famous Buildings'', compare with the [[Mausoleum of Maussollos|Tomb of Mausolus at Halicarnassus]]), with its new zinc-coated stainless steel sheathing, is peaked by a {{convert|20|ft|m|0|adj=on}} glass \"beehive\" ornament containing a blue glass box filled with six 1000-watt lightbulbs which emits a deep blue light, a prominent feature of Chicago's nighttime [[skyline]].<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" /> The beehive is supported by four limestone bisons.<ref name=\"mettower\">{{cite web | title = Metropolitan Tower | publisher = Metropolitan Tower | date = 2007 | url = http://www.themetropolitantower.com/home.asp | accessdate = 2007-11-15 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008224704/http://www.themetropolitantower.com/home.asp | archivedate = 2007-10-08 }}</ref> Because of this ornament, the building is sometimes referred to as the \"Beehive Building.\"<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" />\n\nJust beneath the beehive are four [[carillon]] bells ranging in weight from 1,500 to 7,000 pounds, unused for many years until restored in 1979 for the [[List of pastoral visits of Pope John Paul II outside Italy|Chicago visit]] of [[Pope John Paul II]].<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" /> At one time, the bells chimed the well-known [[Westminster Quarters|Cambridge Quarters]] on the quarter-hours.  The base has been altered from its original design: rectangular window openings replaced giant arches on Michigan Avenue and Jackson Boulevard. At one time, the thirtieth floor was the Straus Tower Observatory, which was open to the public for viewing the city.<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" />\n\nThe original main entrance was a pair of elaborately carved bronze doors set in a marble portal flanked by [[Relief|bas-reliefs]] and used to be in the center of the east side, through the largest of the archways.<ref name=\"emporis\" />\n\nIn 2009, the Metropolitan Tower won a \"Best Adaptive Reuse\" award from the Friends of Downtown, a planning and urban design organization for downtown Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|title=Friends of Downtown|url=http://www.friendsofdowntown.org/?awards|accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Symbolism ==\nThe original owner of the Metropolitan Tower was S. W. Straus and Company, a dealer of investment bonds and one of the leading financers of major real estate in Chicago during the late 19th century and early 20th century.<ref name=\"emporis\" />  The tower's crown has many symbols for characteristics the company wanted to portray.  The pyramid symbolized longevity and permanence and the beehive stood for industry and thrift.  When first installed, the beehive also contained four directional beacons, a metaphor for the company's global reach.  The pyramid is supported by the four bisons, a traditional symbol for the American West.  Straus was hoping to use these symbols to instill trust in their customers, to reassure them that their investments would be handled actively and carefully by an institution that could be trusted over the long term. Ironically, the firm failed during the [[Great Depression]] and closed fewer than ten years after lighting the beacon.<ref>{{cite web | title = Metropolitan Tower | work = Exploring 66 on Foot: In the Loop, Where the Road Begins | url= http://www.windycityroadwarrior.com/GiftShop/BOOK-Hybrid-144-145.pdf | format = pdf | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Area ==\nThe Metropolitan Tower is located a block from the entrance to the [[Art Institute of Chicago|Art Institute]] and is within two blocks of stations for all downtown [[Chicago Transit Authority|CTA]] train lines.  The [[Symphony Center]], [[Millennium Park]], [[Harold Washington Library]], and the [[Lake Michigan]] shore are within a half mile.  The south end of the [[Magnificent Mile]] shopping district is less than a mile away.  Dozens of fine restaurants and other eateries are in the neighborhood, and [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]] is across the street.<ref>[[Google Earth]]</ref>\n\n==Position in Chicago's skyline==\nMetropolitan Tower appears in front of [[Chase Tower (Chicago)]] in the diagram below.\n{{Chicago skyline}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Chicago skyscrapers}}\n{{coord|41|52|41.01|N|87|37|28.65|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1924]]\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Residential condominiums in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Chicago school architecture in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Metropolitan Tower, Chicago in May 2016.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Metropolitan Tower in 2016]]\n'''The Metropolitan Tower''', owned by Metropolitan Properties of Chicago,<ref>{{cite web | title = Britannica building to go condo | work = Chicago Business | publisher = Crain's | date = 2004-06-12 | url = http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=12816&seenIt=1 | accessdate = 2007-11-15 }}</ref> is a [[skyscraper]] located at 310 [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|S. Michigan Avenue]] in [[Chicago|Chicago's]] East [[Chicago Landmark]] [[Historic Michigan Boulevard District]] in the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] in [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], [[Illinois]], United States and has been renovated as a [[condominium]] complex with 242 units.<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\">{{cite news | last = Nunn | first = Emily | title = Blue light special | work = Chicago Tribune| pages = 5:1, 9 | publisher = Tribune Company | date = 2007-11-15 | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/lifestyle/chi-1115accessbeehivenov15,1,370570.story?coll=chi_mezz | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>  Residences range in size from {{convert|1200|sqft|m2}} to {{convert|4000|sqft|m2}}. [[Penthouse apartment|Penthouses]] feature 360 degree city views and private elevators.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Metropolitan Tower |work=Development Details |publisher=Condodomain |date=2006 |url=http://chicago.condodomain.com/user/condos/The-Metropolitan-Tower/1077 |accessdate=2007-11-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913183341/http://chicago.condodomain.com/user/condos/The-Metropolitan-Tower/1077 |archivedate=2007-09-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Prices run from $300,000 for a {{convert|762|sqft|m2}} one-bedroom unit to $1.365 million for a {{convert|1932|sqft|m2}} three-bedroom.<ref>''Chicago Magazine'', January 2005</ref>  The Metropolitan Tower is also home for a branch of [[Chase (bank)|Chase Bank]].\n\n== History ==\nDesigned by [[Graham, Anderson, Probst & White]], the Metropolitan Tower was named the Straus Building when completed in 1924.  Though it was the first building in Chicago with 30 or more floors, it was never officially designated [[List of tallest buildings in Chicago|Chicago's tallest building]] since the [[Chicago Temple Building]], also completed in 1924, is taller by {{convert|92|ft|m}} but has seven fewer floors.<ref name=\"temple\">{{cite web | title = Chicago Temple Building | work = Emporis | publisher = Emporis.com | date = 2007 | url = http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=chicagotemplebuilding-chicago-il-usa | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>  The Straus Building and the Chicago Temple Building were the first to take advantage of the 1923 [[zoning]] ordinance; before then, no building in Chicago could be taller than {{convert|260|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite book |last= Wolfe |first= Gerard R.|title= Chicago In and Around the Loop; Walking Tours of Architecture and History |edition=Second |year=2004 |publisher= McGraw-Hill}}</ref>\n\nThe Metropolitan Tower was at one time called the [[CNA Center|Continental National Insurance Company]] Building (later [[CNA Center|Continental Center I]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forums.tannerworld.com/showthread.php?t=7602 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911235110/http://forums.tannerworld.com/showthread.php?t=7602 |archivedate=2007-09-11 }}</ref>).  From 1980 to 2004 it was called the [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|Britannica Building]] when that company was its tenant.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web | title = Metropolitan Tower | work = Emporis | publisher = Emporis.com | date = 2007 | url = http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=metropolitantower-chicago-il-usa | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics, past and present ==\nThis U-shaped building, standing at {{convert|475|ft|m}} in height, fronts Chicago's [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] and [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]].  The {{convert|40|ft|m|0|adj=on}} [[pyramid]] at the top of the building (which Schulze & Harrington, authors of ''Chicago's Famous Buildings'', compare with the [[Mausoleum of Maussollos|Tomb of Mausolus at Halicarnassus]]), with its new zinc-coated stainless steel sheathing, is peaked by a {{convert|20|ft|m|0|adj=on}} glass \"beehive\" ornament containing a blue glass box filled with six 1000-watt lightbulbs which emits a deep blue light, a prominent feature of Chicago's nighttime [[skyline]].<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" /> The beehive is supported by four limestone bisons.<ref name=\"mettower\">{{cite web | title = Metropolitan Tower | publisher = Metropolitan Tower | date = 2007 | url = http://www.themetropolitantower.com/home.asp | accessdate = 2007-11-15 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008224704/http://www.themetropolitantower.com/home.asp | archivedate = 2007-10-08 }}</ref> Because of this ornament, the building is sometimes referred to as the \"Beehive Building.\"<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" />\n\nJust beneath the beehive are four [[carillon]] bells ranging in weight from 1,500 to 7,000 pounds, unused for many years until restored in 1979 for the [[List of pastoral visits of Pope John Paul II outside Italy|Chicago visit]] of [[Pope John Paul II]].<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" /> At one time, the bells chimed the well-known [[Westminster Quarters|Cambridge Quarters]] on the quarter-hours.  The base has been altered from its original design: rectangular window openings replaced giant arches on Michigan Avenue and Jackson Boulevard. At one time, the thirtieth floor was the Straus Tower Observatory, which was open to the public for viewing the city.<ref name=\"bluelightspecial\" />\n\nThe original main entrance was a pair of elaborately carved bronze doors set in a marble portal flanked by [[Relief|bas-reliefs]] and used to be in the center of the east side, through the largest of the archways.<ref name=\"emporis\" />\n\nIn 2009, the Metropolitan Tower won a \"Best Adaptive Reuse\" award from the Friends of Downtown, a planning and urban design organization for downtown Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|title=Friends of Downtown|url=http://www.friendsofdowntown.org/?awards|accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Symbolism ==\nThe original owner of the Metropolitan Tower was S. W. Straus and Company, a dealer of investment bonds and one of the leading financers of major real estate in Chicago during the late 19th century and early 20th century.<ref name=\"emporis\" />  The tower's crown has many symbols for characteristics the company wanted to portray.  The pyramid symbolized longevity and permanence and the beehive stood for industry and thrift.  When first installed, the beehive also contained four directional beacons, a metaphor for the company's global reach.  The pyramid is supported by the four bisons, a traditional symbol for the American West.  Straus was hoping to use these symbols to instill trust in their customers, to reassure them that their investments would be handled actively and carefully by an institution that could be trusted over the long term. Ironically, the firm failed during the [[Great Depression]] and closed fewer than ten years after lighting the beacon.<ref>{{cite web | title = Metropolitan Tower | work = Exploring 66 on Foot: In the Loop, Where the Road Begins | url= http://www.windycityroadwarrior.com/GiftShop/BOOK-Hybrid-144-145.pdf | format = pdf | accessdate = 2007-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Area ==\nThe Metropolitan Tower is located a block from the entrance to the [[Art Institute of Chicago|Art Institute]] and is within two blocks of stations for all downtown [[Chicago Transit Authority|CTA]] train lines.  The [[Symphony Center]], [[Millennium Park]], [[Harold Washington Library]], and the [[Lake Michigan]] shore are within a half mile.  The south end of the [[Magnificent Mile]] shopping district is less than a mile away.  Dozens of fine restaurants and other eateries are in the neighborhood, and [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]] is across the street.<ref>[[Google Earth]]</ref>\n\n==Position in Chicago's skyline==\nMetropolitan Tower appears in front of [[Chase Tower (Chicago)]] in the diagram below.\n{{Chicago skyline}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Chicago skyscrapers}}\n{{coord|41|52|41.01|N|87|37|28.65|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1924]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Residential condominiums in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Chicago school architecture in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metropolitan_Tower_(Chicago)"}
{"title_page": "Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church", "text_new": "[[File:Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church 3.JPG|thumb|Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church]]\n'''Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church''', originally named the '''Third Church of Christ, Scientist''', is a landmark church located on West Washington Boulevard in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States. The church was built in 1901 by [[Hugh M.G. Garden]]. The church was sold to its current owners in 1947. It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on February 16, 1989,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MetroBaptist.html|title=Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|date=2003|accessdate=2007-06-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607145154/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MetroBaptist.html|archivedate=2007-06-07}}</ref> and was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2016.\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in West Side Chicago]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://metropolitanmbc.tripod.com}}\n\n{{coord|41.883021|-87.681288|region:US-IL_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Chicago Landmark places of worship}}\n{{Near West Side, Chicago}}\n\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1901]]\n[[Category:20th-century Baptist churches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Former Christian Science churches, societies and buildings in Illinois]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Churches on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-church-stub|Chicago=y}}\n{{Chicago-struct-stub}}\n\n[[zh:\u5927\u90fd\u4f1a\u4f20\u6559\u58eb\u6d78\u4fe1\u4f1a\u6559\u5802]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church 3.JPG|thumb|Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church]]\n'''Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church''', originally named the '''Third Church of Christ, Scientist''', is a landmark church located on West Washington Boulevard in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States. The church was built in 1901 by [[Hugh M.G. Garden]]. The church was sold to its current owners in 1947. It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on February 16, 1989,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MetroBaptist.html|title=Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|date=2003|accessdate=2007-06-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607145154/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MetroBaptist.html|archivedate=2007-06-07}}</ref> and was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2016.\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in West Side Chicago]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://metropolitanmbc.tripod.com}}\n\n{{coord|41.883021|-87.681288|region:US-IL_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Chicago Landmark places of worship}}\n{{Near West Side, Chicago}}\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1901]]\n[[Category:20th-century Baptist churches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Former Christian Science churches, societies and buildings in Illinois]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Churches on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-church-stub|Chicago=y}}\n{{Chicago-struct-stub}}\n\n[[zh:\u5927\u90fd\u4f1a\u4f20\u6559\u58eb\u6d78\u4fe1\u4f1a\u6559\u5802]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metropolitan_Missionary_Baptist_Church"}
{"title_page": "William Cobbett", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name= William Cobbett\n|image = William Cobbett.JPG\n|caption = ''William Cobbett'', portrait in oils, possibly by [[George Cooke (painter)|George Cooke]], about 1831 [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]], London\n|birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1763|3|9}}\n|birth_place = [[Farnham]], Surrey, England\n|death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1835|6|18|1763|3|9}}\n|death_place = [[Normandy, Surrey|Normandy]], Surrey, England\n|occupation = [[Pamphleteer]], journalist, soldier\n|movement =\n|notableworks = ''[[Rural Rides]]''\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]\n|party = [[Radicals (UK)|Radical]]\n|term_start = 1832\n|term_end = 1835\n|successor = [[John Frederick Lees]]\n}}\n'''William Cobbett''' (9 March 1763 \u2013 18 June 1835) was an English [[pamphleteer]], farmer, journalist and [[member of parliament]] born in [[Farnham, Surrey]]. He believed that reforming [[Parliament of Great Britain|Parliament]], including abolishing \"[[rotten borough]]s\", would ease the poverty of farm labourers. Relentlessly he sought an end to borough-mongers, [[Sinecure|sinecurists]] and \"tax-eaters\" (meaning a wide class of overpaid or corrupt bureaucrats). Early in life he was a loyal devotee of King and Country, but he later pushed for [[Radicalism (historical)|Radicalism]], which helped bring about the [[Reform Act 1832]] and his election that year as one of two [[member of Parliament|MPs]] for the newly enfranchised borough of [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]. He also strongly advocated of [[Catholic Emancipation]]. His [[polemic]]s cover subjects from political reform to religion. His best known book is ''[[Rural Rides]]'' (1830, still in print).\n\n==Life==\n{{anchor|Early life}}\n===Early life (1763\u20131791)===\n[[File:Farnham Cobbett's birthplace.JPG|250px|thumb|left|William Cobbett's birthplace.]]\nWilliam Cobbett was born in Farnham, Surrey, on 9 March 1763, the third son of George Cobbett (a farmer and publican) and Anne Vincent.<ref name=\"ODNB\">[[Ian Dyck]], '[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5734 Cobbett,  William  (1763\u20131835)]', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004, accessed 23 July 2011.</ref> He was taught to read and write by his father, and he started working from an early age. He later said: \"I do not remember a time when I did not earn my living. My first occupation was, driving small birds from the turnip seed, and the rooks from the peas\".<ref>Daniel Green, ''Great Cobbett: The Noblest Agitator'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1985), pp. 18\u201319.</ref><ref>G. D. H. Cole, ''The Life of William Cobbett'' (Westport: Greenwood Press, 1971), p. 16.</ref> He worked as a farm labourer at [[Farnham Castle]],<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 38.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 16.</ref> and he also worked briefly as a gardener in the King's garden at [[Kew Gardens|Kew]].<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\">Clifford-Smith, S., \"William Cobbett: cottager's friend\", ''Australian Garden History'', 19 (5), 2008, pp. 4\u20136.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 17\u201318.</ref> His rural upbringing also gave him a lifelong love of [[gardening]] and [[hunting]].<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 19, 21, 30.</ref>\n\n[[File:The life of William Cobbett - written by himself. No 2' (William Cobbett) by James Gillray.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Cartoon of Cobbett enlisting in the army. From the ''[[Political Register]]'' of 1809. Artist [[James Gillray]].]]\n\nOn 6 May 1783, on a whim, he took the stage coach to London and spent eight or nine months as a clerk in the employ of a Mr Holland at [[Gray's Inn]].<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 41\u201342.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 22\u201323.</ref> He joined the [[54th (West Norfolk) Regiment of Foot]] during 1783 and made good use of the soldier's copious spare time to educate himself, particularly in English [[grammar]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" /><ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 48\u201349.</ref> Between 1785 and 1791 Cobbett was stationed with his regiment in [[New Brunswick]] and he sailed from [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] in Kent to [[City of Halifax|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]]. Cobbett was in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], [[Fredericton]] and elsewhere in the province until September 1791, being promoted through the ranks to [[sergeant major]], the most senior rank of [[non-commissioned officer]].\n\nCobbett returned to England with his regiment, landing at [[Portsmouth]] on 3 November 1791, and obtained his discharge from the army on 19 December 1791. In [[Woolwich]] during February 1792, he married American-born Anne Reid (1774\u20131848), whom he had met while stationed at Fort Howe in Saint John.<ref>[[John Robert Colombo]] ''Canadian Literary Landmarks'' p47</ref><ref>[http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=810d2953\u20131fd0-4625-b956-717ad9be3568 Jenny's Spring]</ref> His children with her were: Anne Cobbett (1795\u20131877), William Cobbett (1798\u20131878), [[John Morgan Cobbett]] (1800\u20131877), James Paul Cobbett (1803\u20131881), Eleanor Cobbett (1805\u20131900), and Susan Cobbett (1807\u20131889).<ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 437.</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Travels to France and the United States|France and the United States}}\n\n===Refuge in France and the United States (1792\u20131800)===\nCobbett had developed an animosity towards some corrupt [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]]s, and he gathered evidence on the issue while in New Brunswick, but his charges against them were ignored. He wrote ''The Soldier's Friend'' (1792) protesting against the low pay and harsh treatment of enlisted men in the British army.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Sensing that he was about to be indicted in retribution, he fled to France in March 1792 to avoid imprisonment. Cobbett had intended to stay a year to learn the French language, but he found the [[French Revolution]] and the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] in progress, and so he sailed for the United States in September 1792.\n\nHe was first at [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], then [[Philadelphia]] by the spring of 1793. Cobbett initially prospered by teaching English to Frenchmen and translating texts from French into English. He later claimed that he had become a political writer by accident: during an English lesson one of his French students read aloud from a New York newspaper the addresses of welcome that the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] had sent to [[Joseph Priestley]] upon his arrival in America, along with Priestley's replies. His student applauded the anti-British sentiments they contained and he quarrelled with Cobbett, who then resolved to \"write and publish a pamphlet in defence of my country\".<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 125.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 55.</ref> His ''Observations on the Emigration of Dr Priestley'', which was published anonymously in 1794, was a violent attack on the radical Priestley.<ref name=\"Green127\">Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 127.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 57\u221258.</ref>\n\nIn 1795 Cobbett wrote ''A Bone to Gnaw for the Democrats'', which attacked the pro-French Democratic Party.<ref name=\"Green127\" /><ref name=\"Cole59\">Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 59.</ref> He replied to his critics with ''A Kick for a Bite'', which was his first work to be published under the pseudonym \"Peter Porcupine\" (a reviewer had compared him to a [[porcupine]], which pleased him).<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 129.</ref><ref name=\"Cole59\" /> He took the side of the [[Federalist Party|Federalists]], who were led by [[Alexander Hamilton]], because they were more friendly to Britain than the pro-French Democrats led by [[Thomas Jefferson]].<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 130, 132, 133\u221234.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 64.</ref> \n\nIn January 1796 he began a monthly tract under the title of ''The Censor''; this was discontinued after eight numbers, and its place occupied by ''Porcupine's Gazette'', a daily newspaper, which ran from March 1797 until the end of 1799.<ref name=\"DNB\">Edward Smith, \u2018[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Cobbett,_William_(DNB00) Cobbett, William]\u2019, in Leslie Stephen (ed.), ''Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900, Volume XI'' (1887).</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 59\u221260.</ref> [[Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Talleyrand]], at the time a French spy in America, attempted unsuccessfully to bribe Cobbett to the French cause.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 140.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 63.</ref>\n\nCobbett opened a bookstore in Philadelphia in July 1796 and he adorned its shop-window with a large portrait of George III, and its interior with a huge painting of \"[[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]]'s Decisive Victory over the French\". This provocative display attracted considerable publicity and made him famous in America.<ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 62.</ref> He reprinted and published much of the violent loyalist literature then current, including [[George Chalmers (antiquarian)|George Chalmers]]'s hostile biography of [[Thomas Paine]].<ref name=\"DNB\" /><ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 147.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 60.</ref>\n\nCobbett also campaigned against the eminent physician and abolitionist [[Benjamin Rush]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crusader.bac.edu/library/rarebooks/Pride.htm |title=The Pride of Britannia Humbled |last=Cobbett |first=William |year=1817 |publisher=Belmont Abbey College NC USA |accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref> whose advocacy of bleeding during the yellow fever epidemic may have caused many deaths.<ref>{{cite book|first=Alyn|last=Brodsky|year=2004|title=Benjamin Rush: Patriot and Physician}} pp. 337\u2013343.</ref> Rush won a libel lawsuit against Cobbett, who never fully paid the $8,000 judgment, but instead fled to New York and back to England during 1800, via [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], Nova Scotia to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]] in Cornwall.\n\nThe British government was grateful to Cobbett for supporting Britain's interests in America: the [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn|Duke of Kent]] hailed him as \"this great British patriot\"; the British representative in America, [[Robert Liston (diplomat)|Robert Liston]], offered him a \"great pecuniary reward\" (which he turned down); and the [[Secretary at War]], [[William Windham]], said that Cobbett deserved a statue of gold for the services he had rendered to Britain in America.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 141.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 58.</ref>\n\n{{anchor|The Political Register}}\n\n===''The Political Register'' (1800\u20131810)===\nThe government of [[William Pitt the Younger]] offered Cobbett the editorship of a government newspaper, but he refused, as he preferred to remain independent.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> His own paper ''The Porcupine'', bearing the motto \"Fear God, Honour the King\", started up on 30 October 1800, but without success, and he sold his interest in it in 1801.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Less than a month later, however, he started his ''[[Political Register]]'', a weekly newspaper that was published almost every week from January 1802 until 1835, the year of Cobbett's death.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> \n\nWhen war broke out again between Britain and France in May 1803, after the brief [[Peace of Amiens]], [[Napoleon]] [[Napoleon's planned invasion of the United Kingdom|planned to invade]] England and he assembled the [[Grande Arm\u00e9e]] at [[Boulogne]]. In June ''[[The Morning Post]]'' appealed to all newspapers to print articles for the \"purpose of arousing the people to the defence of the country\".<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 231.</ref> Cobbett immediately began his pamphlet ''Important Considerations for the People of the Kingdom'', which warned the country of the consequences of a French invasion. Cobbett turned down an offer of payment from the government and it was published anonymously in July.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 231\u201332.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 81.</ref> The Prime Minister, [[Henry Addington, 1st Viscount Sidmouth|Henry Addington]], ordered copies to be sent to every parish in England and it had an immediate effect on public opinion.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 232\u201335.</ref>\n\nAlthough initially staunchly anti-[[Jacobin]], by 1804 Cobbett was questioning the policies of the Pitt government, especially the immense [[national debt]] and profligate use of [[sinecure]]s that Cobbett believed was ruining the country and increasing class antagonism.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> By 1807 he was endorsing reformers such as [[Francis Burdett]] and [[John Cartwright (political reformer)|John Cartwright]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nCobbett opposed attempts in the House of Commons to introduce bills against [[boxing]] and [[bull-baiting]], writing to [[William Windham]] on 2 May 1804 that the Bill \"goes to the rearing of puritanism into a system\".<ref>[[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]] (ed.), ''The Windham Papers. Volume Two'' (London: Herbert Jenkins Ltd, 1913), p. 234.</ref>\n\nCobbett published the ''Complete Collection of State Trials'' between 1804 and 1812 and amassed accounts of parliamentary debates from 1066 onwards, but sold his shares in it to [[Thomas Curson Hansard|T. C. Hansard]] in 1812 due to financial difficulties.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> This unofficial record of parliamentary proceedings later became known officially as [[Hansard]].\n\nCobbett intended to campaign for Parliament in [[Honiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Honiton]] in 1806, but was persuaded by [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald]] to let him campaign in his stead. Both men campaigned together but failed, having refused to bribe voters by \"buying\" votes. This situation also encouraged his opposition to [[rotten borough]]s and belief in parliamentary reform.<ref>[[David Cordingly]], ''Cochrane the Dauntless: The Life and Adventures of Thomas Cochrane'', Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 2008 ({{ISBN|978-0-7475-8545-9}}), pp. 105\u2013113.</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Prison}}\n\n===Prison (1810\u20131812)===\n[[File:The Hampshire hog in the pound LOC ds.10846.jpg|thumb|The Hampshire hog in the pound]]\nCobbett was found guilty of treasonous [[libel]] on 15 June 1810 after objecting in ''The Register'' to the [[flogging]] at [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] of local [[militia]]men by [[Electorate of Hanover|Hanoverians]]. He was sentenced to two years' imprisonment in [[Newgate Prison]]. While in prison he wrote the pamphlet, ''Paper Against Gold'',<ref>{{cite web |last=Cobbett |first=William |title=Paper Against Gold |url=https://archive.org/details/cobbettspaperaga00cobbrich |work=Cobbett's Paper Against Gold |publisher=California Digital Library |accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref> warning of the dangers of [[Banknote|paper money]], as well as many essays and letters. On his release a dinner was given in his honour in London. Attended by 600 people, it was directed by [[Sir Francis Burdett, 5th Baronet|Sir Francis Burdett]], who, like Cobbett, was an enthusiast for parliamentary reform.\n\n{{anchor|Two-Penny Trash}}\n\n===\"Two-Penny Trash\" (1812\u20131817)===\nBy 1815 the tax on newspapers had reached four [[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|pence]] a copy. As few people could afford to pay six or seven pence for a daily newspaper, the tax restricted the circulation of most journals to those with fairly high incomes. Cobbett could sell only just over a thousand copies a week. Nonetheless, he began criticising [[William Wilberforce]] for his endorsement of the Corn Laws, and for his personal wealth, his opposition to bull and [[bear-baiting]], and particularly for his approval of \"the fat and lazy and laughing and singing negroes\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Eric |last=Metaxas |authorlink=Eric Metaxas |year=2007 |title=Amazing Grace: William Wilberforce and the Heroic Campaign to End Slavery |url=https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta |url-access=registration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta/page/251 251\u2013252]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1816 Cobbett began publishing the ''Political Register'' as a pamphlet. Cobbett now sold the ''Political Register'' for only two pence and it soon had a circulation of 40,000. Critics termed it \"two-penny trash\", a phrase Cobbett adopted.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Cobbett's journal was soon the main newspaper read by the working class. The Radical campaigner [[Samuel Bamford]] later wrote:\n\n<blockquote>At this time the writings of William Cobbett suddenly became of great authority; they were read on nearly every cottage hearth in the manufacturing districts of South Lancashire, in those of Leicester, Derby, and Nottingham; also in many of the Scottish manufacturing towns. Their influence was speedily visible. He directed his readers to the true cause of their sufferings\u2014misgovernment; and to its proper corrective\u2014parliamentary reform.<ref>Samuel Bamford, ''Bamford's Passages in the Life of a Radical, and Early Days: Vol. II'' (London: T. Fisher Unwin, 1905), pp. 11\u201312.</ref><ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 384\u221285.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 211.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis made Cobbett a dangerous man, and he learnt in 1817 that the government was planning to arrest him for [[sedition]]. With the government intending to [[Habeas Corpus Suspension Act 1817|suspend ''habeas corpus'']], and fearing arrest for his arguably seditious writings, Cobbett fled to the United States.<ref name=\"DNB\" /> On Wednesday 27 March 1817, he embarked at [[Liverpool]] for New York on the ship ''Importer'', with D. Ogden as master, accompanied by his two eldest sons, William and John.\n\n===Refuge in the United States (1817\u20131819)===\n[[File:Cobbett - Rural rides in the southern, western and eastern counties of England, 1930 - 5214769.tif|thumb|''Rural rides in the southern, western and eastern counties of England'', 1930.]]\nCobbett lived for two years on a farm on [[Long Island]], where he wrote ''Grammar of the English Language'' and with help from [[William Benbow]], a friend in London, continued to issue the ''Political Register''. He also wrote ''The American Gardener'' (1821), one of the earliest horticultural books published in the United States.<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nCobbett closely observed alcohol-drinking habits in the United States. He stated in 1819, \"Americans preserve their gravity and quietness and good-humour even in their drink.\"  He believed it would be \"far better for them to be as noisy and quarrelsome as the English drunkards; for then the odiousness of the vice would be more visible, and the vice itself might become less frequent.\"<ref>Walters, Ronald G., ''Getting Rid of Demon Alcohol''.</ref>\n\nA plan to return to England with the remains of the British-American radical pamphleteer and revolutionary [[Thomas Paine]] (who had died in 1809) for a proper burial resulted in the ultimate loss of the remains. The plan was to remove them from his [[New Rochelle, New York]] [[Thomas Paine Cottage|farm]] and give Paine a heroic reburial on his native soil, but the bones were still among Cobbett's effects when he died 16 years later. There is no confirmed story of what happened to them after that, although claims to parts of the body have been made down the years, including his skull and right hand.\n\nCobbett arrived back in Britain at Liverpool by ship in November 1819.\n\n{{anchor|Later life}}\n\n===Later life (1819\u20131835)===\nCobbett arrived back in England soon after the [[Peterloo Massacre]]. He joined with other [[Radicalism (historical)|radicals]] in his attacks on the government and was charged with libel three times in the next couple of years.\n\n[[Image:Batteuse 1881.jpg|300px|right|thumb|The introduction of horse-powered threshing machines to farms was one of the principal causes of the [[Swing Riots]].]]\n\nIn 1820, he campaigned for Parliament in [[Coventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry]], but finished last in the poll.  That year he also established a plant nursery at Kensington, where he grew many North American trees, such as the black locust (''Robinia pseudoacacia''), and with his son, a variety of maize he called \"Cobbett's corn\".<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/> This was a dwarf strain found growing in a French cottage garden that turned out to grow well in England's shorter summer. To help sell the variety he issued a book entitled ''A Treatise on Cobbett's Corn'' (1828).<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/> Meanwhile he also wrote his popular ''[[Cottage Economy]]'' (1822), which taught cottagers some skills necessary for self-sufficiency, such as bread-making, beer-brewing, and livestock farming.<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nNot content to let information be brought to him for his newspaper, Cobbett did his own journalistic work \u2013 especially on his repeated theme of the plight of the rural Englishman. He began riding about the country on horseback, observing events in towns and villages. ''[[Rural Rides]]'', a work for which Cobbett is still known, appeared first in serial form in the ''Political Register'' from 1822 to 1826, and then in book form in 1830. While writing ''Rural Rides'', Cobbett also produced ''The Woodlands'' (1825), a book on [[silviculture]].<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nAlthough not a Catholic,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hanink |first=James G |date=November 2005 |title=William Cobbett. By G. K. Chesterton. Review |journal=[[New Oxford Review]] |volume= LXXII |issue= 10 |url=http://www.newoxfordreview.org/briefly.jsp?did=1105-briefly |accessdate=30 March 2009}}</ref> Cobbett at this time also advocated the cause of [[Catholic Emancipation]]. Between 1824 and 1826, he published his ''History of the Protestant Reformation'', a broadside against the traditional [[Protestant]] historical narrative of the British reformation, stressing the lengthy and often bloody persecutions of Catholics in Britain and Ireland. Catholics were still forbidden at that time to enter certain professions or become members of parliament. Although the law was no longer enforced, it was officially still a crime to attend mass or build a Catholic church. Although Wilberforce also worked and spoke against discrimination against Catholics, Cobbett resumed his strident opposition to the noted reformer, particularly after Wilberforce in 1823 published his ''Appeal in Behalf of the Negro Slaves in the West Indies.''<ref>{{cite book |first=Eric |last=Metaxas |authorlink=Eric Metaxas |year=2007 |title=Amazing Grace: William Wilberforce and the Heroic Campaign to End Slavery |url=https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta |url-access=registration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta/page/264 264\u2013265]}}</ref>  Wilberforce, long suffering from ill health, retired the next year.\n[[File:John Doyle 1833 MPs.JPG|200px|right|thumb|William Cobbett (left foreground), [[John Gully]] (middle) and [[Joseph Pease (railway pioneer)|Joseph Pease]] (right) (the first Quaker elected to Parliament) arriving at Westminster, during March 1833.  Sketch by [[John Doyle (artist)|John Doyle]].]]\nIn 1829, Cobbett published ''Advice To Young Men'', in which he criticised ''[[An Essay on the Principle of Population]]'' by the Reverend [[Thomas Robert Malthus]]. That year he also published ''The English Gardener'', which he later updated and expanded. This book has been compared favourably with other contemporary garden tomes, such as [[John Claudius Loudon]]'s ''Encyclop\u00e6dia of Gardening''.<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nCobbett continued to publish controversy in the ''Political Register'' and was charged in July 1831 with [[seditious libel]] for a pamphlet entitled ''Rural War'', endorsing the Captain [[Swing Riots]], in which rioters were smashing farm machinery and burning haystacks. Cobbett successfully conducted his own defence.<ref>State Trials (New Series) II, 789.</ref>\n\nCobbett still sought to be elected to the House of Commons. He was defeated in [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]] in 1826 and in Manchester in 1832, but after the passage of the [[1832 Reform Act]], Cobbett won the seat of [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]. In Parliament, Cobbett concentrated his energies on attacking corruption in government and the [[Poor Law Amendment Act 1834|1834 Poor Law]]. During later life, however, [[Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay]], a fellow [[Member of Parliament|MP]], remarked that Cobbett's faculties were impaired by age; indeed that his [[paranoia]] had reached insanity.\n\nFrom 1831 until his death, Cobbett managed a farm named Ash in the village of [[Normandy, Surrey]], a few miles from his birthplace at [[Farnham]]. Cobbett died there after a brief illness in June 1835 and was buried in the churchyard of St Andrew's Parish Church, Farnham.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nDuring his lifetime Cobbett campaigned for parliament five times, of which four attempts were unsuccessful:\n*1806 [[Honiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Honiton]]\n*1820 [[Coventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry]]\n*1826 [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]]\n*1832 [[Manchester (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester]]\n\nIn 1832 he was successfully elected as member for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]].\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:William Cobbett Grave 2016.jpg|thumb|right|The tomb of William Cobbett in the churchyard of St Andrew's church in Farnham.]]\nCobbett is considered to have begun as an inherently conservative journalist, who angered by the corrupt British political establishment, became increasingly radical and sympathetic to anti-government and democratic ideals. He provided an alternative opinion of rural England in the age of an [[Industrial Revolution]], with which he was not in sympathy. Cobbett wished England would return to the rural England of the 1760s, in which he had been born. Unlike fellow radical Thomas Paine, Cobbett was not an internationalist cosmopolitan and did not endorse a republican Britain. He boasted that he was not a \"citizen of world.... It is quite enough for me to think about what is best for England, Scotland and Ireland\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Possessing a national identity, he often criticised rival countries and warned them that they should not \"swagger about and be saucy to England\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> He said his identification with the Church of England was due in part because it \"bears the name of my country\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> [[Ian Dyck]] claimed that Cobbett endorsed \"the eighteenth-century [[Country Party (Britain)|Country Party]] platform\".<ref>[[Ian Dyck]], 'Introduction' in William Cobbett, ''Rural Rides'' (Penguin Classics, 2005), p. xxiii.</ref> [[Edward Tangye Lean]] described him as \"an archaic English Tory\".<ref>[[Edward Tangye Lean]], ''The Napoleonists. A Study in Political Disaffection. 1760\u20131960'' (London: Oxford University Press, 1970), p. 206.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/articles/herring.htm |title=The Lure of the Red Herring |last=Quinion |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Quinion |work=World Wide Words |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nCobbett has been praised by thinkers of various political persuasions, such as [[Matthew Arnold]], [[Karl Marx]], [[G. K. Chesterton]], [[A. J. P. Taylor]], [[Raymond Williams]], [[E. P. Thompson]] and [[Michael Foot]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> \nA story by Cobbett issued in 1807 coined the term '[[red herring]]' to mean a distraction from an important issue.<ref>Martin Chilton, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9917758/William-Cobbett-forgotten-chronicler-of-England.html William Cobbett: forgotten chronicler of England], The Telegraph, 9 March 2015.</ref>\n\nCobbett's sons were trained as barristers and founded a partnership in Manchester named [[Cobbetts LLP|Cobbetts]] in his honour. The firm dissolved in 2013. His second son [[John Morgan Cobbett]] (1800\u20131877) followed him into politics and like his father became MP for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]].<ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 436.</ref>\n\nCobbett's birthplace, a public house in Farnham once named ''The Jolly Farmer'', has been renamed ''The William Cobbett''. The Brooklyn-based history band [[Pi\u00f1ataland]] performed a song about William Cobbett's quest to rebury [[Thomas Paine]] entitled \"An American Man\". An equestrian statue of Cobbett is planned for a site in Farnham.<ref>BBC [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/surrey/7842303.stm Home town plans statue of Cobbett] 21 January 2009</ref><ref>Waverley Borough Council Committee Document [http://waverweb.waverley.gov.uk/live/wbc/NewComDB.nsf/163fb885c18530cb802575ae003875fd/e953dfbc1b202107802575ae00364b94?OpenDocument William Cobbett Statue]</ref> Farnham has the William Cobbett Junior School named in his honour; its logo is a porcupine.\n\nAfter Cobbett's death, Benjamin Tilly, who had served Cobbett as companion, secretary and factotum, initiated The Cobbett Club. Members sent petitions to Parliament demanding radical reform and produced radical pamphlets and leaflets to keep Cobbett's politics alive. Some of these are still available in libraries. The William Cobbett Society, based in Farnham, produces a yearly edition of 'Cobbett's New Register', and celebrates Cobbett's life, works and spirit in various activities, including an annual Rural Ride and lecture.\n\n{{anchor|Writings|Publications|Books}}\n\n==Works==\n<!--chronological order-->\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Bone to Gnaw for the Democrats |location=Philadelphia |date=1795}}, as \"Peter Porcupine\", reprinted at London in 1797.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001746911 |title=Cobbett's Parliamentary History of England from the Norman conquest in 1066 to the Year 1803, from Which Last-Mentioned Epoch It Is Continued Downwards in the Work Entitled \"Cobbett's Parliamentary Debates\" |location=London |publisher=T.C. Hansard |date=1806\u20131820 |volume=Vols. I{{ndash}}XXXV}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Complete Collection of State Trials and Proceedings for High Treason and Other Crimes and Misdemeanors from the Earliest Period to the Year 1783 |volume=Vols. I, II, III, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eZhJ3I2ik5UC IV], V, VI, VII, VIII, IX, X, XI, XII, XIII, XIV, XV, XVI, XVII, XVIII, XIX, XX, & XXI |location=London |publisher=T.C. Hansard |date=1816}}, with [[Thomas Bayly Howell]].}}\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Grammar of the English Language |location=New York |date=1818 }}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |date=1822 |title=Cottage Economy |publisher=C. Clement|title-link=Cottage Economy }}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/contents_page.jsp?t_id=Cobbett |title=Rural Rides |date=1822 |publisher= |location=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=te4nAAAAYAAJ |title=The Woodlands |date=1825}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=The Housekeeper's Magazine and Family Economist |location=London |publisher=Knight & Lacey |date=1826}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |author2=Juan Enrique Sievrac |display-authors=0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x8qoHHFUKdoC&printsec=frontcover |location=London |publisher=Mills, Jowett, & Mills |title=Elements of the Roman History in English and French from the Foundation of Rome to the Battle of Actium, Selected from the Best Authors, Ancient and Modern, with a Series of Questions at the End of Each Chapter for the Use of Schools and Young Persons in General |date=1828 }}, with [[Juan Enrique Sievrac]].\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://socserv2.mcmaster.ca/~econ/ugcm/3ll3/cobbett/PoorMan'sFriend.pdf |title=The Poor Man's Friend, or, Essays on the Rights and Duties of the Poor |date=1829 |publisher= |location=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_emigrant_s_guide.html?id=H6cNAAAAQAAJ |title=Emigrant's Guide: In Ten Letters, Addressed to the Tax-Payers of England |location=London |publisher=Mills, Jowett, & Mills |date=1829}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |date=1830 |title=Rural Rides in the Counties |publisher=Cobbett}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=The Life of Andrew Jackson, President of the United States |location=New York |publisher=Harper & Bros. |date=1834}}\n\n<!--need dates and publishers-->\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/15510 |title=Advice to Young Men, and (Incidentally) to Young Women, in the Middle and Higher Ranks of Life |date= |location= }}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://www.exclassics.com/protref/protint.htm |title=A History of the Protestant Reformation in England and Ireland |date= |location= |publisher=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://archive.org/details/listabbeysprior00cobbgoog |title=List of Abbeys, Priories, Nunneries, Hospitals, and Other Religious Foundations in England and Wales and in Ireland Confiscated, Seized on, or Alienated by the Protestant \"Reformation\" Sovereigns and Parliaments |date= |location= |publisher=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Year's Residence in the United States of America |publisher=B. Bensley |location=Andover}}.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tilford#Tilford Oak or King's Oak or Novel's Oak|Tilford]], with an ancient oak tree described by Cobbett\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*[[G. D. H. Cole]], ''The Life of William Cobbett'' (Wesport: Greenwood Press, 1971). {{ISBN|0837147816}}\n*Ian Dyck, \"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5734 Cobbett,  William  (1763\u20131835)]\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004, accessed 23 July 2011.\n*Daniel Green, ''Great Cobbett: The Noblest Agitator'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1985). {{ISBN|0192818651}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.journoblog.com/2010/03/cobbetts-rural-rides/ Journoblog]: A Brief History, Analysis and Discussion of Cobbett and Rural Rides\n*[[G. K. Chesterton]], ''William Cobbett'' (1925). {{ISBN|0-7551-0033-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Heath|first=Richard|title=The English Peasant|year=1893|publisher=T. Fisher Unwin|location=London|chapter=[[s:The English Peasant/William Cobbett|William Cobbett]]|pages=245\u2013291}}\n*[[Richard Ingrams]], ''The Life and Adventures of William Cobbett'', (2005) {{ISBN|0-00-255800-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Young |first=Penny|title=Two Cocks on the Dunghill \u2013 William Cobbett and Henry Hunt: their friendship, feuds and fights.|publisher=Twopenny Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-9561703-3-0|url=http://www.twopennypress.co.uk}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|William Cobbett}}\n*[http://www.williamcobbett.org.uk The William Cobbett Society]\n*[http://www.blupete.com/Literature/Biographies/Philosophy/Cobbett.htm Biography by Peter Landry]\n*[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=2809 Biography at the ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online'']\n*[http://www.cse.dmu.ac.uk/~mward/gkc/books/William_Cobbett.txt Biography by G. K. Chesterton]\n*[http://www.spartacus-educational.com/PRcobbett.htm Brief history: gives additional reference to ''The Political Register'']\n*[http://home.vicnet.net.au/~aphea/history.htm History of Hansard]\n*[http://www.weyriver.co.uk/theriver/people_3_names.htm William Cobbett and his home town of Farnham]\n*[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/contents_page.jsp?t_id=Cobbett William Cobbett's Rural Rides on Vision of Britain]\n*{{UK National Archives ID}}\n*[http://www.exclassics.com/protref/protint.htm ''The Protestant Reformation''] Online reading and multiple ebook formats at Ex-classics.\n*{{Hansard-contribs |mr-william-cobbett |William Cobbett }}\n*{{Gutenberg author |id=Cobbett,+William+(1763\u20131835) }}\n*{{Internet Archive author |sname=William Cobbett}}\n*{{Librivox author |id=1932}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n|title = Member of Parliament for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]\n|with = [[John Fielden]]\n|years = [[1832 United Kingdom general election|1832]]\u2013[[1835 United Kingdom general election|1835]]\n}}\n{{s-aft |after = [[John Fielden]] and<br />[[John Frederick Lees]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cobbett, William}}\n[[Category:1763 births]]\n[[Category:1835 deaths]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English essayists]]\n[[Category:English farmers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Farnham]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1832\u20131835]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]]\n[[Category:Linguists of English]]\n[[Category:Burials in Surrey]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:British reformers]]\n[[Category:British male essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century essayists]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name= William Cobbett\n|image = William Cobbett.JPG\n|caption = ''William Cobbett'', portrait in oils, possibly by [[George Cooke (painter)|George Cooke]], about 1831 [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]], London\n|birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1763|3|9}}\n|birth_place = [[Farnham]], Surrey, England\n|death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1835|6|18|1763|3|9}}\n|death_place = [[Normandy, Surrey|Normandy]], Surrey, England\n|occupation = [[Pamphleteer]], journalist, soldier\n|movement =\n|notableworks = ''[[Rural Rides]]''\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]\n|party = [[Radicals (UK)|Radical]]\n|term_start = 1832\n|term_end = 1835\n|successor = [[John Frederick Lees]]\n}}\n'''William Cobbett''' (9 March 1763 \u2013 18 June 1835) was an English [[pamphleteer]], farmer, journalist and [[member of parliament]] born in [[Farnham, Surrey]]. He believed that reforming [[Parliament of Great Britain|Parliament]], including abolishing \"[[rotten borough]]s\", would ease the poverty of farm labourers. Relentlessly he sought an end to borough-mongers, [[Sinecure|sinecurists]] and \"tax-eaters\" (meaning a wide class of overpaid or corrupt bureaucrats). Early in life he was a loyal devotee of King and Country, but he later pushed for [[Radicalism (historical)|Radicalism]], which helped bring about the [[Reform Act 1832]] and his election that year as one of two [[member of Parliament|MPs]] for the newly enfranchised borough of [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]. He also strongly advocated of [[Catholic Emancipation]]. His [[polemic]]s cover subjects from political reform to religion. His best known book is ''[[Rural Rides]]'' (1830, still in print).\n\n==Life==\n{{anchor|Early life}}\n===Early life (1763\u20131791)===\n[[File:Farnham Cobbett's birthplace.JPG|250px|thumb|left|William Cobbett's birthplace.]]\nWilliam Cobbett was born in Farnham, Surrey, on 9 March 1763, the third son of George Cobbett (a farmer and publican) and Anne Vincent.<ref name=\"ODNB\">[[Ian Dyck]], '[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5734 Cobbett,  William  (1763\u20131835)]', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004, accessed 23 July 2011.</ref> He was taught to read and write by his father, and he started working from an early age. He later said: \"I do not remember a time when I did not earn my living. My first occupation was, driving small birds from the turnip seed, and the rooks from the peas\".<ref>Daniel Green, ''Great Cobbett: The Noblest Agitator'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1985), pp. 18\u201319.</ref><ref>G. D. H. Cole, ''The Life of William Cobbett'' (Westport: Greenwood Press, 1971), p. 16.</ref> He worked as a farm labourer at [[Farnham Castle]],<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 38.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 16.</ref> and he also worked briefly as a gardener in the King's garden at [[Kew Gardens|Kew]].<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\">Clifford-Smith, S., \"William Cobbett: cottager's friend\", ''Australian Garden History'', 19 (5), 2008, pp. 4\u20136.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 17\u201318.</ref> His rural upbringing also gave him a lifelong love of [[gardening]] and [[hunting]].<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 19, 21, 30.</ref>\n\n[[File:The life of William Cobbett - written by himself. No 2' (William Cobbett) by James Gillray.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Cartoon of Cobbett enlisting in the army. From the ''[[Political Register]]'' of 1809. Artist [[James Gillray]].]]\n\nOn 6 May 1783, on a whim, he took the stage coach to London and spent eight or nine months as a clerk in the employ of a Mr Holland at [[Gray's Inn]].<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 41\u201342.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 22\u201323.</ref> He joined the [[54th (West Norfolk) Regiment of Foot]] during 1783 and made good use of the soldier's copious spare time to educate himself, particularly in English [[grammar]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" /><ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 48\u201349.</ref> Between 1785 and 1791 Cobbett was stationed with his regiment in [[New Brunswick]] and he sailed from [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] in Kent to [[City of Halifax|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]]. Cobbett was in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], [[Fredericton]] and elsewhere in the province until September 1791, being promoted through the ranks to [[sergeant major]], the most senior rank of [[non-commissioned officer]].\n\nCobbett returned to England with his regiment, landing at [[Portsmouth]] on 3 November 1791, and obtained his discharge from the army on 19 December 1791. In [[Woolwich]] during February 1792, he married American-born Anne Reid (1774\u20131848), whom he had met while stationed at Fort Howe in Saint John.<ref>[[John Robert Colombo]] ''Canadian Literary Landmarks'' p47</ref><ref>[http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=810d2953\u20131fd0-4625-b956-717ad9be3568 Jenny's Spring]</ref> His children with her were: Anne Cobbett (1795\u20131877), William Cobbett (1798\u20131878), [[John Morgan Cobbett]] (1800\u20131877), James Paul Cobbett (1803\u20131881), Eleanor Cobbett (1805\u20131900), and Susan Cobbett (1807\u20131889).<ref name=Cole/>\n\n{{anchor|Travels to France and the United States|France and the United States}}\n\n===Refuge in France and the United States (1792\u20131800)===\nCobbett had developed an animosity towards some corrupt [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]]s, and he gathered evidence on the issue while in New Brunswick, but his charges against them were ignored. He wrote ''The Soldier's Friend'' (1792) protesting against the low pay and harsh treatment of enlisted men in the British army.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Sensing that he was about to be indicted in retribution, he fled to France in March 1792 to avoid imprisonment. Cobbett had intended to stay a year to learn the French language, but he found the [[French Revolution]] and the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] in progress, and so he sailed for the United States in September 1792.\n\nHe was first at [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], then [[Philadelphia]] by the spring of 1793. Cobbett initially prospered by teaching English to Frenchmen and translating texts from French into English. He later claimed that he had become a political writer by accident: during an English lesson one of his French students read aloud from a New York newspaper the addresses of welcome that the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] had sent to [[Joseph Priestley]] upon his arrival in America, along with Priestley's replies. His student applauded the anti-British sentiments they contained and he quarrelled with Cobbett, who then resolved to \"write and publish a pamphlet in defence of my country\".<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 125.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 55.</ref> His ''Observations on the Emigration of Dr Priestley'', which was published anonymously in 1794, was a violent attack on the radical Priestley.<ref name=\"Green127\">Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 127.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 57\u221258.</ref>\n\nIn 1795 Cobbett wrote ''A Bone to Gnaw for the Democrats'', which attacked the pro-French Democratic Party.<ref name=\"Green127\" /><ref name=\"Cole59\">Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 59.</ref> He replied to his critics with ''A Kick for a Bite'', which was his first work to be published under the pseudonym \"Peter Porcupine\" (a reviewer had compared him to a [[porcupine]], which pleased him).<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 129.</ref><ref name=\"Cole59\" /> He took the side of the [[Federalist Party|Federalists]], who were led by [[Alexander Hamilton]], because they were more friendly to Britain than the pro-French Democrats led by [[Thomas Jefferson]].<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 130, 132, 133\u221234.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 64.</ref> \n\nIn January 1796 he began a monthly tract under the title of ''The Censor''; this was discontinued after eight numbers, and its place occupied by ''Porcupine's Gazette'', a daily newspaper, which ran from March 1797 until the end of 1799.<ref name=\"DNB\">Edward Smith, \u2018[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Cobbett,_William_(DNB00) Cobbett, William]\u2019, in Leslie Stephen (ed.), ''Dictionary of National Biography, 1885-1900, Volume XI'' (1887).</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', pp. 59\u221260.</ref> [[Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Talleyrand]], at the time a French spy in America, attempted unsuccessfully to bribe Cobbett to the French cause.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 140.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 63.</ref>\n\nCobbett opened a bookstore in Philadelphia in July 1796 and he adorned its shop-window with a large portrait of George III, and its interior with a huge painting of \"[[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]]'s Decisive Victory over the French\". This provocative display attracted considerable publicity and made him famous in America.<ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 62.</ref> He reprinted and published much of the violent loyalist literature then current, including [[George Chalmers (antiquarian)|George Chalmers]]'s hostile biography of [[Thomas Paine]].<ref name=\"DNB\" /><ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 147.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 60.</ref>\n\nCobbett also campaigned against the eminent physician and abolitionist [[Benjamin Rush]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crusader.bac.edu/library/rarebooks/Pride.htm |title=The Pride of Britannia Humbled |last=Cobbett |first=William |year=1817 |publisher=Belmont Abbey College NC USA |accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref> whose advocacy of bleeding during the yellow fever epidemic may have caused many deaths.<ref>{{cite book|first=Alyn|last=Brodsky|year=2004|title=Benjamin Rush: Patriot and Physician}} pp. 337\u2013343.</ref> Rush won a libel lawsuit against Cobbett, who never fully paid the $8,000 judgment, but instead fled to New York and back to England during 1800, via [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], Nova Scotia to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]] in Cornwall.\n\nThe British government was grateful to Cobbett for supporting Britain's interests in America: the [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn|Duke of Kent]] hailed him as \"this great British patriot\"; the British representative in America, [[Robert Liston (diplomat)|Robert Liston]], offered him a \"great pecuniary reward\" (which he turned down); and the [[Secretary at War]], [[William Windham]], said that Cobbett deserved a statue of gold for the services he had rendered to Britain in America.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 141.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 58.</ref>\n\n{{anchor|The Political Register}}\n\n===''The Political Register'' (1800\u20131810)===\nThe government of [[William Pitt the Younger]] offered Cobbett the editorship of a government newspaper, but he refused, as he preferred to remain independent.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> His own paper ''The Porcupine'', bearing the motto \"Fear God, Honour the King\", started up on 30 October 1800, but without success, and he sold his interest in it in 1801.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Less than a month later, however, he started his ''[[Political Register]]'', a weekly newspaper that was published almost every week from January 1802 until 1835, the year of Cobbett's death.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> \n\nWhen war broke out again between Britain and France in May 1803, after the brief [[Peace of Amiens]], [[Napoleon]] [[Napoleon's planned invasion of the United Kingdom|planned to invade]] England and he assembled the [[Grande Arm\u00e9e]] at [[Boulogne]]. In June ''[[The Morning Post]]'' appealed to all newspapers to print articles for the \"purpose of arousing the people to the defence of the country\".<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', p. 231.</ref> Cobbett immediately began his pamphlet ''Important Considerations for the People of the Kingdom'', which warned the country of the consequences of a French invasion. Cobbett turned down an offer of payment from the government and it was published anonymously in July.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 231\u201332.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 81.</ref> The Prime Minister, [[Henry Addington, 1st Viscount Sidmouth|Henry Addington]], ordered copies to be sent to every parish in England and it had an immediate effect on public opinion.<ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 232\u201335.</ref>\n\nAlthough initially staunchly anti-[[Jacobin]], by 1804 Cobbett was questioning the policies of the Pitt government, especially the immense [[national debt]] and profligate use of [[sinecure]]s that Cobbett believed was ruining the country and increasing class antagonism.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> By 1807 he was endorsing reformers such as [[Francis Burdett]] and [[John Cartwright (political reformer)|John Cartwright]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nCobbett opposed attempts in the House of Commons to introduce bills against [[boxing]] and [[bull-baiting]], writing to [[William Windham]] on 2 May 1804 that the Bill \"goes to the rearing of puritanism into a system\".<ref>[[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]] (ed.), ''The Windham Papers. Volume Two'' (London: Herbert Jenkins Ltd, 1913), p. 234.</ref>\n\nCobbett published the ''Complete Collection of State Trials'' between 1804 and 1812 and amassed accounts of parliamentary debates from 1066 onwards, but sold his shares in it to [[Thomas Curson Hansard|T. C. Hansard]] in 1812 due to financial difficulties.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> This unofficial record of parliamentary proceedings later became known officially as [[Hansard]].\n\nCobbett intended to campaign for Parliament in [[Honiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Honiton]] in 1806, but was persuaded by [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald]] to let him campaign in his stead. Both men campaigned together but failed, having refused to bribe voters by \"buying\" votes. This situation also encouraged his opposition to [[rotten borough]]s and belief in parliamentary reform.<ref>[[David Cordingly]], ''Cochrane the Dauntless: The Life and Adventures of Thomas Cochrane'', Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 2008 ({{ISBN|978-0-7475-8545-9}}), pp. 105\u2013113.</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Prison}}\n\n===Prison (1810\u20131812)===\n[[File:The Hampshire hog in the pound LOC ds.10846.jpg|thumb|The Hampshire hog in the pound]]\nCobbett was found guilty of treasonous [[libel]] on 15 June 1810 after objecting in ''The Register'' to the [[flogging]] at [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] of local [[militia]]men by [[Electorate of Hanover|Hanoverians]]. He was sentenced to two years' imprisonment in [[Newgate Prison]]. While in prison he wrote the pamphlet, ''Paper Against Gold'',<ref>{{cite web |last=Cobbett |first=William |title=Paper Against Gold |url=https://archive.org/details/cobbettspaperaga00cobbrich |work=Cobbett's Paper Against Gold |publisher=California Digital Library |accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref> warning of the dangers of [[Banknote|paper money]], as well as many essays and letters. On his release a dinner was given in his honour in London. Attended by 600 people, it was directed by [[Sir Francis Burdett, 5th Baronet|Sir Francis Burdett]], who, like Cobbett, was an enthusiast for parliamentary reform.\n\n{{anchor|Two-Penny Trash}}\n\n===\"Two-Penny Trash\" (1812\u20131817)===\nBy 1815 the tax on newspapers had reached four [[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|pence]] a copy. As few people could afford to pay six or seven pence for a daily newspaper, the tax restricted the circulation of most journals to those with fairly high incomes. Cobbett could sell only just over a thousand copies a week. Nonetheless, he began criticising [[William Wilberforce]] for his endorsement of the Corn Laws, and for his personal wealth, his opposition to bull and [[bear-baiting]], and particularly for his approval of \"the fat and lazy and laughing and singing negroes\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Eric |last=Metaxas |authorlink=Eric Metaxas |year=2007 |title=Amazing Grace: William Wilberforce and the Heroic Campaign to End Slavery |url=https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta |url-access=registration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta/page/251 251\u2013252]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1816 Cobbett began publishing the ''Political Register'' as a pamphlet. Cobbett now sold the ''Political Register'' for only two pence and it soon had a circulation of 40,000. Critics termed it \"two-penny trash\", a phrase Cobbett adopted.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Cobbett's journal was soon the main newspaper read by the working class. The Radical campaigner [[Samuel Bamford]] later wrote:\n\n<blockquote>At this time the writings of William Cobbett suddenly became of great authority; they were read on nearly every cottage hearth in the manufacturing districts of South Lancashire, in those of Leicester, Derby, and Nottingham; also in many of the Scottish manufacturing towns. Their influence was speedily visible. He directed his readers to the true cause of their sufferings\u2014misgovernment; and to its proper corrective\u2014parliamentary reform.<ref>Samuel Bamford, ''Bamford's Passages in the Life of a Radical, and Early Days: Vol. II'' (London: T. Fisher Unwin, 1905), pp. 11\u201312.</ref><ref>Green, ''Great Cobbett'', pp. 384\u221285.</ref><ref>Cole, ''Life of William Cobbett'', p. 211.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis made Cobbett a dangerous man, and he learnt in 1817 that the government was planning to arrest him for [[sedition]]. With the government intending to [[Habeas Corpus Suspension Act 1817|suspend ''habeas corpus'']], and fearing arrest for his arguably seditious writings, Cobbett fled to the United States.<ref name=\"DNB\" /> On Wednesday 27 March 1817, he embarked at [[Liverpool]] for New York on the ship ''Importer'', with D. Ogden as master, accompanied by his two eldest sons, William and John.\n\n===Refuge in the United States (1817\u20131819)===\n[[File:Cobbett - Rural rides in the southern, western and eastern counties of England, 1930 - 5214769.tif|thumb|''Rural rides in the southern, western and eastern counties of England'', 1930.]]\nCobbett lived for two years on a farm on [[Long Island]], where he wrote ''Grammar of the English Language'' and with help from [[William Benbow]], a friend in London, continued to issue the ''Political Register''. He also wrote ''The American Gardener'' (1821), one of the earliest horticultural books published in the United States.<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nCobbett closely observed alcohol-drinking habits in the United States. He stated in 1819, \"Americans preserve their gravity and quietness and good-humour even in their drink.\"  He believed it would be \"far better for them to be as noisy and quarrelsome as the English drunkards; for then the odiousness of the vice would be more visible, and the vice itself might become less frequent.\"<ref>Walters, Ronald G., ''Getting Rid of Demon Alcohol''.</ref>\n\nA plan to return to England with the remains of the British-American radical pamphleteer and revolutionary [[Thomas Paine]] (who had died in 1809) for a proper burial resulted in the ultimate loss of the remains. The plan was to remove them from his [[New Rochelle, New York]] [[Thomas Paine Cottage|farm]] and give Paine a heroic reburial on his native soil, but the bones were still among Cobbett's effects when he died 16 years later. There is no confirmed story of what happened to them after that, although claims to parts of the body have been made down the years, including his skull and right hand.\n\nCobbett arrived back in Britain at Liverpool by ship in November 1819.\n\n{{anchor|Later life}}\n\n===Later life (1819\u20131835)===\nCobbett arrived back in England soon after the [[Peterloo Massacre]]. He joined with other [[Radicalism (historical)|radicals]] in his attacks on the government and was charged with libel three times in the next couple of years.\n\n[[Image:Batteuse 1881.jpg|300px|right|thumb|The introduction of horse-powered threshing machines to farms was one of the principal causes of the [[Swing Riots]].]]\n\nIn 1820, he campaigned for Parliament in [[Coventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry]], but finished last in the poll.  That year he also established a plant nursery at Kensington, where he grew many North American trees, such as the black locust (''Robinia pseudoacacia''), and with his son, a variety of maize he called \"Cobbett's corn\".<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/> This was a dwarf strain found growing in a French cottage garden that turned out to grow well in England's shorter summer. To help sell the variety he issued a book entitled ''A Treatise on Cobbett's Corn'' (1828).<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/> Meanwhile he also wrote his popular ''[[Cottage Economy]]'' (1822), which taught cottagers some skills necessary for self-sufficiency, such as bread-making, beer-brewing, and livestock farming.<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nNot content to let information be brought to him for his newspaper, Cobbett did his own journalistic work \u2013 especially on his repeated theme of the plight of the rural Englishman. He began riding about the country on horseback, observing events in towns and villages. ''[[Rural Rides]]'', a work for which Cobbett is still known, appeared first in serial form in the ''Political Register'' from 1822 to 1826, and then in book form in 1830. While writing ''Rural Rides'', Cobbett also produced ''The Woodlands'' (1825), a book on [[silviculture]].<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nAlthough not a Catholic,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hanink |first=James G |date=November 2005 |title=William Cobbett. By G. K. Chesterton. Review |journal=[[New Oxford Review]] |volume= LXXII |issue= 10 |url=http://www.newoxfordreview.org/briefly.jsp?did=1105-briefly |accessdate=30 March 2009}}</ref> Cobbett at this time also advocated the cause of [[Catholic Emancipation]]. Between 1824 and 1826, he published his ''History of the Protestant Reformation'', a broadside against the traditional [[Protestant]] historical narrative of the British reformation, stressing the lengthy and often bloody persecutions of Catholics in Britain and Ireland. Catholics were still forbidden at that time to enter certain professions or become members of parliament. Although the law was no longer enforced, it was officially still a crime to attend mass or build a Catholic church. Although Wilberforce also worked and spoke against discrimination against Catholics, Cobbett resumed his strident opposition to the noted reformer, particularly after Wilberforce in 1823 published his ''Appeal in Behalf of the Negro Slaves in the West Indies.''<ref>{{cite book |first=Eric |last=Metaxas |authorlink=Eric Metaxas |year=2007 |title=Amazing Grace: William Wilberforce and the Heroic Campaign to End Slavery |url=https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta |url-access=registration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/amazinggrace00meta/page/264 264\u2013265]}}</ref>  Wilberforce, long suffering from ill health, retired the next year.\n[[File:John Doyle 1833 MPs.JPG|200px|right|thumb|William Cobbett (left foreground), [[John Gully]] (middle) and [[Joseph Pease (railway pioneer)|Joseph Pease]] (right) (the first Quaker elected to Parliament) arriving at Westminster, during March 1833.  Sketch by [[John Doyle (artist)|John Doyle]].]]\nIn 1829, Cobbett published ''Advice To Young Men'', in which he criticised ''[[An Essay on the Principle of Population]]'' by the Reverend [[Thomas Robert Malthus]]. That year he also published ''The English Gardener'', which he later updated and expanded. This book has been compared favourably with other contemporary garden tomes, such as [[John Claudius Loudon]]'s ''Encyclop\u00e6dia of Gardening''.<ref name=\"Clifford-Smith, S. 2008, pp. 4-6\"/>\n\nCobbett continued to publish controversy in the ''Political Register'' and was charged in July 1831 with [[seditious libel]] for a pamphlet entitled ''Rural War'', endorsing the Captain [[Swing Riots]], in which rioters were smashing farm machinery and burning haystacks. Cobbett successfully conducted his own defence.<ref>State Trials (New Series) II, 789.</ref>\n\nCobbett still sought to be elected to the House of Commons. He was defeated in [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]] in 1826 and in Manchester in 1832, but after the passage of the [[1832 Reform Act]], Cobbett won the seat of [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]. In Parliament, Cobbett concentrated his energies on attacking corruption in government and the [[Poor Law Amendment Act 1834|1834 Poor Law]]. During later life, however, [[Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay]], a fellow [[Member of Parliament|MP]], remarked that Cobbett's faculties were impaired by age; indeed that his [[paranoia]] had reached insanity.\n\nFrom 1831 until his death, Cobbett managed a farm named Ash in the village of [[Normandy, Surrey]], a few miles from his birthplace at [[Farnham]]. Cobbett died there after a brief illness in June 1835 and was buried in the churchyard of St Andrew's Parish Church, Farnham.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nDuring his lifetime Cobbett campaigned for parliament five times, of which four attempts were unsuccessful:\n*1806 [[Honiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Honiton]]\n*1820 [[Coventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry]]\n*1826 [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]]\n*1832 [[Manchester (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester]]\n\nIn 1832 he was successfully elected as member for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]].\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:William Cobbett Grave 2016.jpg|thumb|right|The tomb of William Cobbett in the churchyard of St Andrew's church in Farnham.]]\nCobbett is considered to have begun as an inherently conservative journalist, who angered by the corrupt British political establishment, became increasingly radical and sympathetic to anti-government and democratic ideals. He provided an alternative opinion of rural England in the age of an [[Industrial Revolution]], with which he was not in sympathy. Cobbett wished England would return to the rural England of the 1760s, in which he had been born. Unlike fellow radical Thomas Paine, Cobbett was not an internationalist cosmopolitan and did not endorse a republican Britain. He boasted that he was not a \"citizen of world.... It is quite enough for me to think about what is best for England, Scotland and Ireland\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> Possessing a national identity, he often criticised rival countries and warned them that they should not \"swagger about and be saucy to England\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> He said his identification with the Church of England was due in part because it \"bears the name of my country\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> [[Ian Dyck]] claimed that Cobbett endorsed \"the eighteenth-century [[Country Party (Britain)|Country Party]] platform\".<ref>[[Ian Dyck]], 'Introduction' in William Cobbett, ''Rural Rides'' (Penguin Classics, 2005), p. xxiii.</ref> [[Edward Tangye Lean]] described him as \"an archaic English Tory\".<ref>[[Edward Tangye Lean]], ''The Napoleonists. A Study in Political Disaffection. 1760\u20131960'' (London: Oxford University Press, 1970), p. 206.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/articles/herring.htm |title=The Lure of the Red Herring |last=Quinion |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Quinion |work=World Wide Words |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nCobbett has been praised by thinkers of various political persuasions, such as [[Matthew Arnold]], [[Karl Marx]], [[G. K. Chesterton]], [[A. J. P. Taylor]], [[Raymond Williams]], [[E. P. Thompson]] and [[Michael Foot]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> \nA story by Cobbett issued in 1807 coined the term '[[red herring]]' to mean a distraction from an important issue.<ref>Martin Chilton, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9917758/William-Cobbett-forgotten-chronicler-of-England.html William Cobbett: forgotten chronicler of England], The Telegraph, 9 March 2015.</ref>\n\nCobbett's sons were trained as barristers and founded a partnership in Manchester named [[Cobbetts LLP|Cobbetts]] in his honour. The firm dissolved in 2013. His second son [[John Morgan Cobbett]] (1800\u20131877) followed him into politics and like his father became MP for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]].<ref name=Cole>G D H Cole, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t_nFBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT504&lpg=PT504&dq ''The Life of William Cobbett''], Routledge (2011) - Google Books pg. </ref>\n\nCobbett's birthplace, a public house in Farnham once named ''The Jolly Farmer'', has been renamed ''The William Cobbett''. The Brooklyn-based history band [[Pi\u00f1ataland]] performed a song about William Cobbett's quest to rebury [[Thomas Paine]] entitled \"An American Man\". An equestrian statue of Cobbett is planned for a site in Farnham.<ref>BBC [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/surrey/7842303.stm Home town plans statue of Cobbett] 21 January 2009</ref><ref>Waverley Borough Council Committee Document [http://waverweb.waverley.gov.uk/live/wbc/NewComDB.nsf/163fb885c18530cb802575ae003875fd/e953dfbc1b202107802575ae00364b94?OpenDocument William Cobbett Statue]</ref> Farnham has the William Cobbett Junior School named in his honour; its logo is a porcupine.\n\nAfter Cobbett's death, Benjamin Tilly, who had served Cobbett as companion, secretary and factotum, initiated The Cobbett Club. Members sent petitions to Parliament demanding radical reform and produced radical pamphlets and leaflets to keep Cobbett's politics alive. Some of these are still available in libraries. The William Cobbett Society, based in Farnham, produces a yearly edition of 'Cobbett's New Register', and celebrates Cobbett's life, works and spirit in various activities, including an annual Rural Ride and lecture.\n\n{{anchor|Writings|Publications|Books}}\n\n==Works==\n<!--chronological order-->\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Bone to Gnaw for the Democrats |location=Philadelphia |date=1795}}, as \"Peter Porcupine\", reprinted at London in 1797.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001746911 |title=Cobbett's Parliamentary History of England from the Norman conquest in 1066 to the Year 1803, from Which Last-Mentioned Epoch It Is Continued Downwards in the Work Entitled \"Cobbett's Parliamentary Debates\" |location=London |publisher=T.C. Hansard |date=1806\u20131820 |volume=Vols. I{{ndash}}XXXV}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Complete Collection of State Trials and Proceedings for High Treason and Other Crimes and Misdemeanors from the Earliest Period to the Year 1783 |volume=Vols. I, II, III, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eZhJ3I2ik5UC IV], V, VI, VII, VIII, IX, X, XI, XII, XIII, XIV, XV, XVI, XVII, XVIII, XIX, XX, & XXI |location=London |publisher=T.C. Hansard |date=1816}}, with [[Thomas Bayly Howell]].}}\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Grammar of the English Language |location=New York |date=1818 }}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |date=1822 |title=Cottage Economy |publisher=C. Clement|title-link=Cottage Economy }}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/contents_page.jsp?t_id=Cobbett |title=Rural Rides |date=1822 |publisher= |location=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=te4nAAAAYAAJ |title=The Woodlands |date=1825}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=The Housekeeper's Magazine and Family Economist |location=London |publisher=Knight & Lacey |date=1826}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |author2=Juan Enrique Sievrac |display-authors=0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x8qoHHFUKdoC&printsec=frontcover |location=London |publisher=Mills, Jowett, & Mills |title=Elements of the Roman History in English and French from the Foundation of Rome to the Battle of Actium, Selected from the Best Authors, Ancient and Modern, with a Series of Questions at the End of Each Chapter for the Use of Schools and Young Persons in General |date=1828 }}, with [[Juan Enrique Sievrac]].\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://socserv2.mcmaster.ca/~econ/ugcm/3ll3/cobbett/PoorMan'sFriend.pdf |title=The Poor Man's Friend, or, Essays on the Rights and Duties of the Poor |date=1829 |publisher= |location=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_emigrant_s_guide.html?id=H6cNAAAAQAAJ |title=Emigrant's Guide: In Ten Letters, Addressed to the Tax-Payers of England |location=London |publisher=Mills, Jowett, & Mills |date=1829}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |date=1830 |title=Rural Rides in the Counties |publisher=Cobbett}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=The Life of Andrew Jackson, President of the United States |location=New York |publisher=Harper & Bros. |date=1834}}\n\n<!--need dates and publishers-->\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/15510 |title=Advice to Young Men, and (Incidentally) to Young Women, in the Middle and Higher Ranks of Life |date= |location= }}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=http://www.exclassics.com/protref/protint.htm |title=A History of the Protestant Reformation in England and Ireland |date= |location= |publisher=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |url=https://archive.org/details/listabbeysprior00cobbgoog |title=List of Abbeys, Priories, Nunneries, Hospitals, and Other Religious Foundations in England and Wales and in Ireland Confiscated, Seized on, or Alienated by the Protestant \"Reformation\" Sovereigns and Parliaments |date= |location= |publisher=}}.\n*{{citation |last=Cobbett |first=William |authorlink=William Cobbett |display-authors=0 |title=A Year's Residence in the United States of America |publisher=B. Bensley |location=Andover}}.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tilford#Tilford Oak or King's Oak or Novel's Oak|Tilford]], with an ancient oak tree described by Cobbett\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*[[G. D. H. Cole]], ''The Life of William Cobbett'' (Wesport: Greenwood Press, 1971). {{ISBN|0837147816}}\n*Ian Dyck, \"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5734 Cobbett,  William  (1763\u20131835)]\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004, accessed 23 July 2011.\n*Daniel Green, ''Great Cobbett: The Noblest Agitator'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1985). {{ISBN|0192818651}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.journoblog.com/2010/03/cobbetts-rural-rides/ Journoblog]: A Brief History, Analysis and Discussion of Cobbett and Rural Rides\n*[[G. K. Chesterton]], ''William Cobbett'' (1925). {{ISBN|0-7551-0033-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Heath|first=Richard|title=The English Peasant|year=1893|publisher=T. Fisher Unwin|location=London|chapter=[[s:The English Peasant/William Cobbett|William Cobbett]]|pages=245\u2013291}}\n*[[Richard Ingrams]], ''The Life and Adventures of William Cobbett'', (2005) {{ISBN|0-00-255800-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Young |first=Penny|title=Two Cocks on the Dunghill \u2013 William Cobbett and Henry Hunt: their friendship, feuds and fights.|publisher=Twopenny Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-9561703-3-0|url=http://www.twopennypress.co.uk}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|William Cobbett}}\n*[http://www.williamcobbett.org.uk The William Cobbett Society]\n*[http://www.blupete.com/Literature/Biographies/Philosophy/Cobbett.htm Biography by Peter Landry]\n*[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=2809 Biography at the ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online'']\n*[http://www.cse.dmu.ac.uk/~mward/gkc/books/William_Cobbett.txt Biography by G. K. Chesterton]\n*[http://www.spartacus-educational.com/PRcobbett.htm Brief history: gives additional reference to ''The Political Register'']\n*[http://home.vicnet.net.au/~aphea/history.htm History of Hansard]\n*[http://www.weyriver.co.uk/theriver/people_3_names.htm William Cobbett and his home town of Farnham]\n*[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/text/contents_page.jsp?t_id=Cobbett William Cobbett's Rural Rides on Vision of Britain]\n*{{UK National Archives ID}}\n*[http://www.exclassics.com/protref/protint.htm ''The Protestant Reformation''] Online reading and multiple ebook formats at Ex-classics.\n*{{Hansard-contribs |mr-william-cobbett |William Cobbett }}\n*{{Gutenberg author |id=Cobbett,+William+(1763\u20131835) }}\n*{{Internet Archive author |sname=William Cobbett}}\n*{{Librivox author |id=1932}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n|title = Member of Parliament for [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]]\n|with = [[John Fielden]]\n|years = [[1832 United Kingdom general election|1832]]\u2013[[1835 United Kingdom general election|1835]]\n}}\n{{s-aft |after = [[John Fielden]] and<br />[[John Frederick Lees]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cobbett, William}}\n[[Category:1763 births]]\n[[Category:1835 deaths]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English essayists]]\n[[Category:English farmers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Farnham]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1832\u20131835]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]]\n[[Category:Linguists of English]]\n[[Category:Burials in Surrey]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:British reformers]]\n[[Category:British male essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century essayists]]\n", "name_user": "Britannicus", "label": "safe", "comment": "page numbers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Cobbett"}
{"title_page": "Robert Weston (disambiguation)", "text_new": "'''[[Robert Weston]]''' is Lord Chancellor of Ireland.\n\n'''Robert Weston''' is also the name of:\n\n*[[Robert Paul Weston]] (born 1975), author\n*[[R. P. Weston]] (Robert Patrick Weston), songwriter\n*[[Bob Weston]] (born 1965), American musician, producer and recording engineer\n*[[Bob Weston (guitarist)]] (1947\u20132012), British musician, briefly guitarist and songwriter with the rock band Fleetwood Mac\n\n==See also==\n*{{in title|Robert Weston}}\n\n{{hndis|Weston, Robert}}\n", "text_old": "'''[[Robert Weston]]''' is Lord Chancellor of Ireland.\n\n'''Robert Weston''' is also the name of:\n\n*[[Robert Paul Weston]] (born 1975), author\n*[[Robert Patrick Weston]], songwriter\n*[[Bob Weston]] (born 1965), American musician, producer and recording engineer\n*[[Bob Weston (guitarist)]] (1947\u20132012), British musician, briefly guitarist and songwriter with the rock band Fleetwood Mac\n\n==See also==\n*{{in title|Robert Weston}}\n\n{{hndis|Weston, Robert}}\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Redirect bypass fromRobert Patrick WestontoR. P. Westonusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Weston_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "Mather Tower", "text_new": "[[File:Mather Tower, Chicago in May 2016.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Mather Tower in 2016]]\n[[File:333 North Michigan, 360 North Michigan and 35 East Wacker.JPG|thumb|150px|left|[[333 North Michigan]], [[360 North Michigan]], Mather Tower and [[35 East Wacker]]]]\n\n'''Mather Tower''' (later '''Lincoln Tower''', as designated on the [[Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District]] roster; now identified primarily by its address) is a [[Neo-Gothic]], [[terra cotta]]-clad high-rise structure in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States.  It is located at 75 East [[Wacker Drive]] in the downtown \"loop\" area, adjacent to the [[Chicago River]].\n\nThe 521-foot-high building is sometimes called \"The Inverted Spyglass\" by Chicagoans due to its highly unusual design, an 18-story octagonal tower atop a more conventional 24-story rectangular \"box.\"   Briefly the tallest building in Chicago at the time of its completion in 1928, it remains the city's most slender high-rise structure at only 100 by 65 feet at its base.  The interior space within the upper octagonal spire contains the least square footage per floor of any Chicago [[skyscraper]].<ref name=\"mather\">The Mather Tower. [http://www.american-architecture.info/USA/CHICAGO/CHIC-LS/CHIC-LS-046.htm Essential American Architecture.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917191815/http://american-architecture.info/USA/CHICAGO/CHIC-LS/CHIC-LS-046.htm |date=2010-09-17 }} Retrieved 2010-08-09.</ref>\n\nIt was designed by Herbert Hugh Riddle (1875\u20131939), the architect of the [[Chicago Theological Seminary]],<ref name=\"McBrien\">McBrien, Judith Paine. [https://books.google.com/books?id=MpgmzOocCmMC&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=Herbert+Hugh+Riddle&source=bl&ots=4XbTVghp24&sig=SSZ05Cg0YRxJB_ZCHb3O-16YgQ4&hl=en&ei=BFFgTIaLGoK78gaP7qC2DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=Herbert%20Hugh%20Riddle&f=false Pocket Guide to Chicago Architecture. (Norton, 2004).] {{ISBN|0-393-73155-3}}. Retrieved 2010-08-09.</ref> as headquarters for the [[Mather Stock Car Company]], a builder of rail cars for transporting livestock. Its design was greatly influenced by the pioneering Chicago Zoning Ordinance of 1923, which placed no limit on the height of new buildings as long as the surface area of the structure's uppermost floor did not exceed 25% of its footprint.  This resulted in a multitude of tall, slender, \"setback\" towers, of which the Mather is an extreme and unusual example.  The top floor of the octagonal spire has only {{convert|280|sqft|m2}} of floor space.<ref name=\"McBrien\"/>\n\nMather Company's founder, [[Alonzo Mather]] (a descendant of [[Cotton Mather]]) is said to be responsible for a number of the building's distinctive design features, including the octagonal tower.<ref name=\"McBrien\"/>  Initial plans called for construction of a second, identical building on [[North Michigan Avenue]], behind the Mather and connected to it by a ground-floor arcade, but onset of the Great Depression in 1929 forced its cancellation.<ref name=\"McBrien\"/>\n\nBy the 1990s the building had fallen into significant disrepair. In 2000 the 4-story \"cupola\" at the top of the building was demolished because of structural deterioration and safety concerns, after chunks of terra cotta began falling from the facade.<ref>Construction Begins on Mather Tower Cupola. [http://www.emporis.com/en/bu/nc/ne/?id=100689 Emporis] Retrieved 2010-08-09.</ref> Damage was sufficiently extensive that consideration was given to dismantling the remaining 17 stories of the octagonal spire as well.<ref name=\"mather\"/>\n\nIn 2000 Masterworks Development Corporation purchased the structure and undertook a complete restoration.  In November 2002, the final phase of the project was initiated when a helicopter lifted the steel framework for a new cupola from a river barge to the top of the tower.<ref>Mather Tower image compilation. [http://www.emporis.com/images/details/171686/exterior-climbing-with-the-top-piece] Retrieved August 23, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe lower, rectangular portion of the building currently houses the River Hotel, while the octagonal upper stories are occupied by a branch of the [[Club Quarters]] chain of membership corporate accommodations.\n\nMather Tower was designated a [[List of Chicago Landmarks|Chicago Historic Landmark]] in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MatherTower.html |title=Mather Tower |work=Chicago Landmarks |publisher=City of Chicago |year=2003 |accessdate=2007-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028111343/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MatherTower.html |archivedate=2007-10-28 }}</ref> and in 2006 it received a National Preservation Honor Award from the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]].<ref>{{cite press release | title =National Trust Presents National Preservation Honor Award to Mather Tower in Chicago | publisher =National Trust for Historic Preservation | date =2006-11-02 | url =http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/awards/national-preservation-awards/mar-tower-2006.html | accessdate = 2006-11-06 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.chicagoarchitecture.info/Building/1066/Mather_Tower.php, Page at ChicagoArchitecture.info]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071028111343/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MatherTower.html Chicago Landmarks: Mather Tower]\n* [http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=116704 Emporis listing]\n\n{{Chicago skyscrapers}}\n{{Chicago Landmark skyscrapers}}\n{{coord|41.8877|-87.6254|type:landmark_region:US-IL|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1928]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago school architecture in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mather Tower, Chicago in May 2016.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Mather Tower in 2016]]\n[[File:333 North Michigan, 360 North Michigan and 35 East Wacker.JPG|thumb|150px|left|[[333 North Michigan]], [[360 North Michigan]], Mather Tower and [[35 East Wacker]]]]\n\n'''Mather Tower''' (later '''Lincoln Tower''', as designated on the [[Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District]] roster; now identified primarily by its address) is a [[Neo-Gothic]], [[terra cotta]]-clad high-rise structure in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States.  It is located at 75 East [[Wacker Drive]] in the downtown \"loop\" area, adjacent to the [[Chicago River]].\n\nThe 521-foot-high building is sometimes called \"The Inverted Spyglass\" by Chicagoans due to its highly unusual design, an 18-story octagonal tower atop a more conventional 24-story rectangular \"box.\"   Briefly the tallest building in Chicago at the time of its completion in 1928, it remains the city's most slender high-rise structure at only 100 by 65 feet at its base.  The interior space within the upper octagonal spire contains the least square footage per floor of any Chicago [[skyscraper]].<ref name=\"mather\">The Mather Tower. [http://www.american-architecture.info/USA/CHICAGO/CHIC-LS/CHIC-LS-046.htm Essential American Architecture.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917191815/http://american-architecture.info/USA/CHICAGO/CHIC-LS/CHIC-LS-046.htm |date=2010-09-17 }} Retrieved 2010-08-09.</ref>\n\nIt was designed by Herbert Hugh Riddle (1875\u20131939), the architect of the [[Chicago Theological Seminary]],<ref name=\"McBrien\">McBrien, Judith Paine. [https://books.google.com/books?id=MpgmzOocCmMC&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=Herbert+Hugh+Riddle&source=bl&ots=4XbTVghp24&sig=SSZ05Cg0YRxJB_ZCHb3O-16YgQ4&hl=en&ei=BFFgTIaLGoK78gaP7qC2DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=Herbert%20Hugh%20Riddle&f=false Pocket Guide to Chicago Architecture. (Norton, 2004).] {{ISBN|0-393-73155-3}}. Retrieved 2010-08-09.</ref> as headquarters for the [[Mather Stock Car Company]], a builder of rail cars for transporting livestock. Its design was greatly influenced by the pioneering Chicago Zoning Ordinance of 1923, which placed no limit on the height of new buildings as long as the surface area of the structure's uppermost floor did not exceed 25% of its footprint.  This resulted in a multitude of tall, slender, \"setback\" towers, of which the Mather is an extreme and unusual example.  The top floor of the octagonal spire has only {{convert|280|sqft|m2}} of floor space.<ref name=\"McBrien\"/>\n\nMather Company's founder, [[Alonzo Mather]] (a descendant of [[Cotton Mather]]) is said to be responsible for a number of the building's distinctive design features, including the octagonal tower.<ref name=\"McBrien\"/>  Initial plans called for construction of a second, identical building on [[North Michigan Avenue]], behind the Mather and connected to it by a ground-floor arcade, but onset of the Great Depression in 1929 forced its cancellation.<ref name=\"McBrien\"/>\n\nBy the 1990s the building had fallen into significant disrepair. In 2000 the 4-story \"cupola\" at the top of the building was demolished because of structural deterioration and safety concerns, after chunks of terra cotta began falling from the facade.<ref>Construction Begins on Mather Tower Cupola. [http://www.emporis.com/en/bu/nc/ne/?id=100689 Emporis] Retrieved 2010-08-09.</ref> Damage was sufficiently extensive that consideration was given to dismantling the remaining 17 stories of the octagonal spire as well.<ref name=\"mather\"/>\n\nIn 2000 Masterworks Development Corporation purchased the structure and undertook a complete restoration.  In November 2002, the final phase of the project was initiated when a helicopter lifted the steel framework for a new cupola from a river barge to the top of the tower.<ref>Mather Tower image compilation. [http://www.emporis.com/images/details/171686/exterior-climbing-with-the-top-piece] Retrieved August 23, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe lower, rectangular portion of the building currently houses the River Hotel, while the octagonal upper stories are occupied by a branch of the [[Club Quarters]] chain of membership corporate accommodations.\n\nMather Tower was designated a [[List of Chicago Landmarks|Chicago Historic Landmark]] in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MatherTower.html |title=Mather Tower |work=Chicago Landmarks |publisher=City of Chicago |year=2003 |accessdate=2007-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028111343/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MatherTower.html |archivedate=2007-10-28 }}</ref> and in 2006 it received a National Preservation Honor Award from the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]].<ref>{{cite press release | title =National Trust Presents National Preservation Honor Award to Mather Tower in Chicago | publisher =National Trust for Historic Preservation | date =2006-11-02 | url =http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/awards/national-preservation-awards/mar-tower-2006.html | accessdate = 2006-11-06 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.chicagoarchitecture.info/Building/1066/Mather_Tower.php, Page at ChicagoArchitecture.info]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071028111343/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/M/MatherTower.html Chicago Landmarks: Mather Tower]\n* [http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=116704 Emporis listing]\n\n{{Chicago skyscrapers}}\n{{Chicago Landmark skyscrapers}}\n{{coord|41.8877|-87.6254|type:landmark_region:US-IL|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1928]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago school architecture in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/